Scanpy Tutorial

Abstract¶

 Scanpy is a versatile tool designed for single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) data analysis. It offers a wide range of functionalities for quality control, visualization, clustering, and annotation of single-cell data, making it a valuable resource for exploring cellular heterogeneity and gene expression patterns. For more information, please visit the Scanpy Website.

1. Setup¶

Return to Index

 This process consists of steps from data download to setting up the analysis environment and separating the Tenet input. Data is in AnnData format, and various variables should be adjusted according to your specific data, so I recommend referring to the Scanpy website for detailed instructions.

Additionally, the Structure of AnnData is as follows.¶

1-1. Data Download¶

Download the data in the terminal environment before proceeding with the setup. For detailed instructions, refer to the following code. The data consists of 3k PBMCs obtained from a healthy donor and is available through 10x Genomics. The data is structured as a 2700 x 32738 Matrix of cells by genes.

In [1]:
# !mkdir data

# !cd data; tar -xzf pbmc3k_filtered_gene_bc_matrices.tar.gz
# !mkdir write

2. Preprocessing¶

Return to Index

 Before diving into the actual analysis, several QC steps are undertaken. In this tutorial, there are roughly three main processes, each as follows. Before following the code and proceeding with the tutorial, it is recommended that you determine your own QC criteria based on your own judgment and experience, as they may vary depending on your specific dataset.

  • Basic filtering
  • Quality control
  • Normalization and Logarithmize

___

This process is finding the top 20 highly expressed genes.

In [7]:
sc.pl.highest_expr_genes(adata, n_top=20, )

normalizing counts per cell
    finished (0:00:00)

2-1. Basic filtering¶

We perform cell filtering based on the number of expressed genes and counts, as well as gene filtering based on the number of cells or counts. This process is conducted to filter out unreliable observations, as cells with too few counts are considered to be dying cells.

In [8]:
sc.pp.filter_cells(adata, min_genes=200)
sc.pp.filter_genes(adata, min_cells=3) 

filtered out 19024 genes that are detected in less than 3 cells

2-2. Quality Control¶

We conduct QC to Remove Low-Quality data. We calculate the QC matrix, and if a high number of mitochondrial genes are detected, we consider these cells to be dying and remove them. Low counts and genes also indicate cells that have not progressed well, so we filter them out based on specific criteria.

In [9]:
adata.var['mt'] = adata.var_names.str.startswith('MT-') 
sc.pp.calculate_qc_metrics(adata, qc_vars=['mt'], percent_top=None, log1p=False, inplace=True)

The rightmost plot represents the proportion of mitochondrial genes.

In [10]:
sc.pl.violin(adata, ['n_genes_by_counts', 'total_counts', 'pct_counts_mt'],
             jitter=0.4, multi_panel=True)

This Scatter plot has been generated to visualize feature-feature relationships.

In [11]:
sc.pl.scatter(adata, x='total_counts', y='pct_counts_mt')
sc.pl.scatter(adata, x='total_counts', y='n_genes_by_counts')

Remove cells that have mitochondrial counts above 5% or total counts over than 2500. It is acceptable to apply different criteria for filtering in downstream analysis if you want. Furthermore, plotting with the data that underwent QC analysis will reveal the adjusted appearance.

In [12]:
adata = adata[adata.obs.n_genes_by_counts < 2500, :]
adata = adata[adata.obs.pct_counts_mt < 5, :]

Designate the Raw Count matrix separately as input for Tenet. This is because Scanpy does not save separately, and the term 'raw data' mentioned here refers to Logarithmized data.

2-3. Normalization and Logarithmize¶

scRNA sequencing often has a high number of zero counts, making it necessary to apply appropriate normalization methods.

In [15]:
sc.pp.normalize_total(adata, target_sum=1e4)
sc.pp.log1p(adata)

normalizing counts per cell
    finished (0:00:00)

3. Dimension Reduction¶

Return to Index

 It can be challenging to analyze an extensive number of genes comprehensively. Therefore, we select important genes and undergo a dimensionality reduction process using this gene subset. The criteria for selecting important genes, which we will explain later, often rely on Standard Deviation. Genes with high STD are referred to as Highly Variable genes (HVGs), and we continue the analysis using this group.


___

3-1. Feature Selection¶

To select important genes, we choose genes with high STD. Typically, 1000 to 5000 highly variable genes (HVGs) are selected. From this point onwards, since we will be working with HVGs, a separate process for storing raw data is necessary. We will describe this later.

In [16]:
sc.pp.highly_variable_genes(adata, min_mean=0.0125, max_mean=3, min_disp=0.5) 
sc.pl.highly_variable_genes(adata) 

extracting highly variable genes
    finished (0:00:00)
--> added
    'highly_variable', boolean vector (adata.var)
    'means', float vector (adata.var)
    'dispersions', float vector (adata.var)
    'dispersions_norm', float vector (adata.var)

3-2. Data Scaling¶

This process is storing the Normalized and Logarithmized Data separately and using only the highly-variable genes to reduce and work.

In [17]:
adata.raw = adata
adata = adata[:, adata.var.highly_variable]

Perform Regression using total count and MT count and Data Scaling. This process is not include in Seurat.

In [18]:
sc.pp.regress_out(adata, ['total_counts', 'pct_counts_mt'])
sc.pp.scale(adata, max_value=10) 

regressing out ['total_counts', 'pct_counts_mt']
    sparse input is densified and may lead to high memory use
    finished (0:00:03)

3-3. PCA¶

In PCA, we utilize Principal Components, which are new variables created by linear combinations of the expression levels of the selected genes from feature selection. It can be used as a pre-processing step for non-linear dimensionality reduction methods.

In [19]:
sc.tl.pca(adata, svd_solver='arpack') 
sc.pl.pca(adata, color='CST3')

computing PCA
    on highly variable genes
    with n_comps=50
    finished (0:00:00)

Heuristically, the elbow method is used to determine how many principal components to use in PCA.

In [20]:
sc.pl.pca_variance_ratio(adata, log=True)

4. Differentially Expressed Genes Analysis¶

Return to Index

 In this process, we proceed with the next steps, such as UMAP, based on the results of clustering. Therefore, it's crucial for the User to Determine How many PCA to use by observing the elbow graph in the previous steps before performing clustering. After clustering, we hope to identify Differentially Expressed Genes successfully.


___

4-1. Clustering¶

Clustering is performed Using Neighbors as part of the process for cell type annotation. This step is crucial because well-done clustering is essential for the success of subsequent analyses.

In [21]:
sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_neighbors=10, n_pcs=40) 

computing neighbors
    using 'X_pca' with n_pcs = 40
    finished: added to `.uns['neighbors']`
    `.obsp['distances']`, distances for each pair of neighbors
    `.obsp['connectivities']`, weighted adjacency matrix (0:00:02)

4-2. UMAP¶

UMAP and t-SNE are both tools developed for visualization. They can describe the dataset in 2D or 3D. However, t-SNE has limitations in preserving large-scale information such as cluster relationships. In other words, t-SNE may not capture the global structure effectively. Therefore, UMAP is used to Divide Cell Types and Visualize where the Samples Originate from.

If you do not wish to use raw data, use this option. (Raw data means scaled data.)

  • use_raw=False
In [22]:
sc.tl.umap(adata) 
sc.pl.umap(adata, color=['CST3', 'NKG7', 'PPBP'])

computing UMAP
    finished: added
    'X_umap', UMAP coordinates (adata.obsm) (0:00:02)

Use the Leiden algorithm, an improved version of the Louvain algorithm. Leiden graph-clustering method is community detection based on optimizing modularity.

In [23]:
sc.tl.leiden(adata)
sc.pl.umap(adata, color=['leiden', 'CST3', 'NKG7'])

running Leiden clustering
    finished: found 8 clusters and added
    'leiden', the cluster labels (adata.obs, categorical) (0:00:00)

4-3. Finding Marker Genes¶

Marker genes are meaningful Biological Labels that characteristics of clusters. To identify such marker genes, we conduct differential expression testing. This involves comparing the cells from one specific cluster to cells from all other clusters, pair by pair, using the Wilcoxon rank-sum test to find significant differences.

If you want to compare two clusters, please refer to thsi code.

  • sc.tl.rank_genes_groups(adata, 'leiden', groups=['0'], reference='1', method='wilcoxon')
  • sc.pl.rank_genes_groups(adata, groups=['0'], n_genes=20)
In [24]:
sc.tl.rank_genes_groups(adata, 'leiden', method='wilcoxon') 
sc.pl.rank_genes_groups(adata, n_genes=25, sharey=False)

ranking genes
    finished: added to `.uns['rank_genes_groups']`
    'names', sorted np.recarray to be indexed by group ids
    'scores', sorted np.recarray to be indexed by group ids
    'logfoldchanges', sorted np.recarray to be indexed by group ids
    'pvals', sorted np.recarray to be indexed by group ids
    'pvals_adj', sorted np.recarray to be indexed by group ids (0:00:01)

The score is a measure from the Wilcoxon rank-sum test, where a higher score indicates a lower p-value and higher expression. We examine the top ranked genes for each of the 8 clusters.

5. Annotation¶

Return to Index

 By examining the marker genes obtained in the previous steps, you can designate the cell type representative of each cluster. This way, you can specify cell types and create result data that can be utilized when using PAGA later on.


___

5-1. Define a list of Marker Genes¶

Identifying cell types automatically can be challenging, so it is often done Manually. Combining the results of DE testing and automated cluster annotation is a common approach that current best parctice. If you are interested in an automated annotation method, please refer to this LINK1, LINK2.

Whether to merge clusters or keep them is depending on user's judgment. Use can make that judgment based on the heatmap. If you want to merge clusters, please refer to the following code.

  • adata.obs = adata.obs.replace({'leiden' : 3 } , 0) # cluster 3 is merged into cluster 0.
In [26]:
sc.pl.rank_genes_groups_heatmap(adata, n_genes = 5 ,swap_axes=True, key="rank_genes_groups", groupby="leiden")

    using 'X_pca' with n_pcs = 50
Storing dendrogram info using `.uns['dendrogram_leiden']`

Specify the genes you want to see then you can visualize them as violin plots for various clusters.

5-3. Save the result¶

This is the Gene select process for Raw count matrix. We will filter and use genes that meet the specified criteria.

In [31]:
deg_names = pd.DataFrame(adata.uns['rank_genes_groups']['names'])
logfoldchanges = pd.DataFrame(adata.uns['rank_genes_groups']['logfoldchanges'])
pvals_adj = pd.DataFrame(adata.uns['rank_genes_groups']['pvals_adj'])

We will filter and use genes that meet the specified criteria.

In [32]:
selected_genes = deg_names[(logfoldchanges >= 0.25) & (pvals_adj <= 0.05)]
Unique_deg_list = selected_genes.stack().unique().tolist()

This is Raw Count matrix for Tenet input.

DEG_raw_count_matrix = raw_count_matrix.loc[:, Unique_deg_list]
DEG_raw_count_matrix.to_csv('/home/Users/write/DEG_raw_count_matrix.csv')
